PMID== 23839528
TI  == effects of c-reactive protein on the neutrophil respiratory burst in vitro.
AB  == this study determined the influence of physiologically relevant concentrations of c-reactive protein (crp) on reactive oxygen species (ros) production by neutrophils. neutrophils from healthy individuals were incubated with soluble pentameric crp prior to tlr stimulation with fusobacterium nucleatum, or fcgammar stimulation with igg-opsonised staphylococcus aureus or heat-aggregated igg. ros  generation by unstimulated cells and those after stimulation were determined using luminol, isoluminol and lucigenin chemiluminescence, detecting predominantly intracellular hypochlorous acid (hocl), extracellular hydrogen peroxide (detected as hocl) and extracellular superoxide respectively. baseline (unstimulated) neutrophil ros generation and release was reduced compared with vehicle control by 10 microg/ml crp. there was no consistent effect of crp on fcgammar-stimulated hocl production, but the extracellular superoxide response was reduced by 10 microg/ml crp. by contrast, crp reduced intracellular (10 microg/ml) and extracellular (3 and 10 microg/ml) hocl generation, but increased  superoxide release (1-10 microg/ml) in response to tlr stimulation. physiologically relevant concentrations of crp inhibited baseline ros generation  and reduced fcgammar-stimulated extracellular superoxide and tlr-stimulated hocl  release, suggesting that crp may offer some degree of host protection from neutrophil-associated, low-level oxidative stress. however, crp enhanced tlr-mediated superoxide release from neutrophils, potentially increasing oxidative stress but aiding host protection from infection.
